segments.text: No worry.
If I get off the track leading to something else that I wanted to weave in, if you don't like the direction I'm going, jerk my chain.
Okay, okay, we're testing.
This is March 7, 2002.
We're out at Harper's Ferry in Nantucket, and I have the privilege and joy of interviewing Paul Lemming.
Paul, to begin this, give a biographical sketch of young Paul Lemming and his family before you came to enroll at Texas A&M.
I was born in Russellville, Arkansas, a little town at that time of about 4,000 people.
I was born on the 3rd of October, 1929, exactly two weeks before the big stock market crash leading to the Great Depression.
The town of Russellville was named for my great-great-grandfather, John Russell, who was a physician and founded the town.
We left Russellville in 1940, moved to Fort Smith, Arkansas for a couple of years, and then moved to Little Rock, Arkansas in 1943.
My father had been a traveling salesman with McKesson Robbins Drug Corporation, and an opening came up in the Houston office, which he thought was better for our family, better economically.
I started Albert Sidney Johnston Junior High School in Houston.
And shortly thereafter, we moved to Nacogdoches when my dad got a permanent territory.
We set up housekeeping there in December of 1943.
We lived there until 1945, February.
And we moved to Beaumont, where my dad got a better territory.
And I finished high school in Beaumont, Texas.
And then...
Which, I know what high school, but this tape doesn't.
Which high school did you finish?
Beaumont High School.
Beaumont High.
How big was that, your senior class, you remember?
Our senior class was 256 seniors.
And your special extracurricular activities when you were at Beaumont High?
I guess you would say athletics.
That was athletics and studying and hunting and fishing, sleeping, whatever I had the chance.
And, of course, I liked to date girls and dance.
Now, I know that you were a superb hurdler.
What else, what other sports?
I was on the all-district football team.
I was a tailback on offense and played safety and halfback on defense.
Everybody played two ways in those days.
Now, you graduated in spring of 48.
Why did you come to Texas A&M?
What led you to be here instead of some other place?
I had 50-some-odd offers of scholarships to different levels of universities throughout the United States, including the two military academies.
Oklahoma, Oklahoma A&M.
It was in those days.
And I had pretty well narrowed the field down to Texas A&M and the University of Texas.
I thought an awful lot of Coach Clyde Littlefield, who was the coach at TU at that time, and also Colonel Andy, Frank Anderson, who was the coach here at Texas A&M.
And I was having difficulty sorting the two out.
Sports writer's accounts of the battle were rather ambiguous.

Buddy Davis, Walter Davis, who later became an All-American basketball player and an Olympian in the high jump, he and I were two very highly sought-after athletes, and we were having trouble making up our minds.
He was at Nederland?
He was at Nederland.
And I had just about decided to go to Texas.
The state track meet was held on the 14th and 15th of May in 1948.
And I went down there with my team from Beaumont.
And we had a very good showing.
And I won the high hurdles and the low hurdles.
New World's record, the low hurdles.
And on a lark I entered the 220 and placed fourth in the state 220.
And that night, since I was in Austin, Coach Littlefield said, I want you to come out to such and such a fraternity house and meet some of the fraternity boys out there.
They're going to be your brothers.
And I said, well, OK.
I'd love to.
And so I went out to this.
fraternity party, I don't recall what the Greek letters were.
And they said, boy, we sure hope you pledge our fraternity.
I said, really, why is that?
They said, boy, with your academic credentials and your athletic credentials, it'll sure look good on our roster.
And I said, why is that important?
And they said, well, fraternities are rated by
the names and the academic qualifications, athletic qualifications that their pledges have, and it'd sure make our fraternity look good.
And I said, let me make sure I got this straight.
You want me to come to the University of Texas not because I can get a good education here, but because I'll make your fraternity look good.
Is that right?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, that's right.
I said, okay, thank you very much.
So I went back home, and I thought about that for a while.
And about the second week of June, I called up Colonel Andy and asked him if the scholarship offer was still open.
He said, oh, yes, it is.
About that time, Charlie Babcock, class of 1920, A&M,
had been working on me pretty hard.
And he had started a letter writing campaign to everybody he could think of.
And all of a sudden these letters start pouring in.
What did those letters in general, what did they say?
They said, talked about what a great school Texas A&M was.
They talked about the fraternity,
of Texas A&M.
They talked about what it meant to be an Aggie.
There's a spirit that can never be told.
That's about the size of it.
I thought about that.
I have a book right over there.
those letters in it that Charlie Babcock put together for me.
As you look back on all those letters, did anybody even hint at anything by the standards of that day or this one that were inappropriate?
Nobody offered you any money?
No, absolutely not.
Nobody offered a car or anything else?
No.
Nobody ever even hinted at that kind of a thing.
They just talked about what an experience.
Now, am I over-quoting what you told me after the Austin muster?
What I thought and what I think I remembered you told me that Charlie Babcock said was that you're too fine a person to go to the University of Texas.
You ought to go to Texas A&M.
Well, pretty much those same words.
Describe, let's stay with Mr. Babcock a minute.
Describe him physically and personality and activities.
Charlie Babcock was about, oh, I'd say 5'8", 5'9", slightly rotund, receding hairline, jovial, always had a joke.
In fact, it's hard to talk to him sometimes because
He kept wanting to tell different kinds of jokes.
But a better-hearted person never existed.
Now, he worked at one of the refineries?
No.
Charlie Babcock was Mr. Insurance in Beaumont.
He had C.L.
Babcock and Sons Insurance Agency downtown on the Pearlstein Building.
And he had two sons who went to A&M.
One of them was a class of 45, and the other one, another I think was a class of 42.
And they were killed early in their adult careers.
One of the boys was killed in a Jeep accident.
That's what I've heard.
Overseas, and I don't recall how the other boy died, but it was a very tragic thing.
He had no surviving children, did he?
No, he and Bess.
He had no other surviving children.
Wait a minute.
He may have had a daughter.
Now, my memory may be fuzzy, but Wirus told me I thought that they had a daughter who died of an unknown heart problem as a little kid on the playground.
That rings a bell.
Because I then ventured the thought that he transferred the love he'd had for his children
to his school, and that was his, and that A&M, in effect, was his big family.
I'd say that's a very accurate assessment.
The, all right, did you let him know when you decided you were going to come to A&M, did you let him know?
He was the second person, I tell you.
The first, no, he was the third.
The first person I told was Colonel Andy.
The second person I told was Clyde Littlefield.
And Charlie Babcock was the third.
How did each, what was the reaction of each of those three?
You called them, I presume?
I called Colonel Andy.
He was delighted.
Coach Littlefield was coming through Beaumont to talk to the Texas exes there in Beaumont.
until his visit.
It was a funny and ironic thing about his visit.
There was a big picture in the paper on the sports page and a big story about all these letters and everything.
Coach Littlefield came out to my house and he sat on the front porch with me and my folks and I told him that I decided to go to
Texas, not to Texas A&M, and he said, well, why?
And I had a stack of letters.
I said, there's over 300 letters here.
He said, we could have gotten you a thousand letters.
I said, yes, sir, but you didn't.
And he just got up and walked off.
And then when you told Mr. Babcock, what was his reaction?
I can't repeat what he said.
He was very happy.
All right.
Had you been up to visit the campus before then, the A&M campus?
Oh, yes, yes.
What was your impression of visiting when you came?
What did it seem like?
Very friendly.
I stayed in the dorm.
The athletes were not staying at Hart Hall at that time.
I came up here in the fall of 47 to attend a football game.
And it was the Arkansas game.
And I stayed in the dorm.
And I went to the mess hall and I ate with the troops on the training table.
I mean, it was just like being with a bunch of good old boys.
Now, which dorm did they live in then?
I think it was Leggett.
Okay.
And so they ate in Sevesa.
Yeah.
All the athletes ate in Sevesa.
The next year, all of the athletes moved into Hart Hall, which was large enough to accommodate everybody.
At that time, we were still getting a lot of veterans back.
And, uh, could you turn that off for a second?
When you, when you came to enroll,
that freshman year, fall of 48. Who brought you?
How'd you get here?
What did you bring with you?
My folks brought me, and we came by car.
I had a footlocker, and we called it a go-to-hell bag, a little overnight thing about so long you'd buy in Walgreens to use when you're hitchhiking back and forth.
to home or to a court trip or something like that.
What was in that footlocker in that bag?
The footlocker, there was one bedspread, one pillow, two pillowcases, four sheets, toilet articles,

port shirt, a couple pairs of slacks, oh, I had, I carried a suit on a hanger, and a couple pairs of shoes, and various and sundry other small items of that nature, and a dictionary, and a typewriter.
A typewriter, hey.
Came in very handy.
As you either in the car coming up here or as they got ready to leave, did your parents give you any special words of advice?
If they did, I don't remember.
They always found me to be very self-reliant.
I was an only child, and I got all the love and affection in the world.
So there were no warnings or advice to go to class and
They never had to worry about that.
Now, you had done well in academics.
Where were you in the senior class at Beaumont High?
I was number two.
Number two.
Did they call it salutatorian in those days?
They did.
I was not the salutatorian.
I was number two academically according to grade point.
Oh, okay.
But the Beaumont Independent School District
required any of those who wanted to stand for valedictorian or salutatorian to take an additional test.
And I told them I wasn't going to take that test, and my record stood on its own, and that I felt that the test that they administered was too biased toward liberal arts and literature.
Although I was an avid reader, I was
I leaned more toward physics and math and that kind of thing, and I felt, I just, I told them I wouldn't untake it because it's biased.
Now, I'm looking not at hindsight now, but at the time you arrived, how well did you think Beaumont High had prepared you for college academically?
At the time I arrived, I wasn't sure because I didn't know what the curriculum was going to be here.
But as I went more and more into the curriculum, I felt that I had the best possible education I could get.
What did you think you were going to major in when you first got here?
I had thought about majoring in engineering, mechanical engineering.
This was when I was still in high school.
But then as I looked at the curriculum more and more and looked at what I was
going to have to devote my time to in athletics, I decided that perhaps some other line of study would be better.
And at that time, Dean John Paul Abbott, who was dean of the School of Arts and Sciences, had convinced the administration that we needed to start a separate business school
Business courses had been taught under the aegis of the arts and sciences.
And he formed a department, not a school, we weren't big enough to have a school, a department of business administration, and I was in the first class.
Oh, okay, good.
Now, in high school you had played football.
Were you planning to go out for any other sports other than track here at A&M?
Oh, I definitely wanted to play football.
But I was the first pure track athlete to come to Texas A&M on a four-year scholarship.
Now, one other person preceded me, but he was not a track man.
He was a field man.
His name was George Cadera, class of 1950.
K-A-D-E-R. K-A-D-E-R-A, George Cadera.
What did your scholarship, in fact, consist of?
Room, board, books, tuition, fees?
And $10 a month for laundry.
Okay.
As a matter of fact Whoop, whoop, remember you've got that on.
Yeah.
Oh, okay.
That's what I made sure I had.
Oh, oh.
As a matter of fact, as the saying goes, funny you should ask.
Oh, you saved all those goodies.
Here is my registration.
My goodness.
For the fall semester of 1950.
Matriculation, $25.
Medical, that's with good old mom, Claghorn, $5.50.
Student activities, I don't know what that is, $1.
Student activities, $9.20.
Key deposit, $1.
Room rent, $11.35.
And laundry, $3.65.
Mm-hmm, mm-hmm.
And just as an aside, when I got my senior ring, it cost $29.84.
Well, I have a request for you to consider.
Whenever you decide that you want to part with those, please pass them on to the archives in the Cushing Library where they would be preserved forever.
I'd be very surprised if they didn't have it already.
Well, but they don't have, you'd be surprised at how some of that stuff.
If they don't have it, they're welcome to.
Because they'd love to.
That question that you asked me, I warned you that I might get off on a track.
No, that's good.
What was that original question again?
It was about what the scholarship consisted of.
Well, you answered that yourself.
In those days, where did you get the books?
Physically, where were they?
We got them from old Army Luke.
The procedure was that you went down to the athletic department.
Bones Urban was the AD at that time.
And Dog Dawson was the assistant AD for business matters, I'll call it.
and you went down to Dog's office and you got a chit from Dog and you took that chit up to H.L.
Heaton's registrar office and you said, Mr. Heaton, here it is and he would make out a receipt like this and give it to you and Dog would also give you another chit and you would go up to J.E.
Lupo, the old Army Lou's office
only store at that time at Northgate, right next door to Doc Lipscomb's drugstore.
And you'd say, hoo-ah!
And you'd hear a hoo-ah from the back and you'd take that chit up there and, Lou, I need to get some books.
Yes, sir.
What do you need?
Here's my registration form.
Give me the books that I need for these courses.
And he'd produce them.
And at the end of the semester, you'd
turn the books back in, get a chip, take the chip back down to the Dawson, turn it in, athletic department would get credit for that.
Now, back to getting here, when you arrived, how did you learn where your room was and what outfit you were in and so forth?
I'd already been assigned that.
I got a letter from Colonel Andy, which is in that book of letters and also in my scrapbooks, which are by your left elbow there, and it told
everything that you should bring, the recommended things.
And it said, don't worry about a whole lot of clothes.
The Corps is going to take care of that.
And they did.
How long did it take after you got here to go get those clothes?
How many?
Well, I think about the next day after I got here, they took us over to the Corpsmaster, and we were issued
the Army officer's uniforms.
And then after that, I'll digress slightly.
All of the athletic freshmen were housed on campus.
Non-athletic freshmen were housed out at the Bryan Army Air Force Base annex.
So you were the only freshman on campus?
We were the only freshman on campus, and there's another tale to that.
But for the first week, we had freshman orientation, and it was all done out at Bryan Annex.
It wasn't logistically feasible to do two sets of... Oh, describe that.
That's your orientation.
We had freshman orientation out there, and basically what they did was give us a series of tests
I mean, each high school forwarded your transcripts to the college, but at that time there was no standardized form of identifying students or what they could do.
The degree of difficulty level of the courses they took in high school, some little one-room high schools would have different curricula from the larger high schools, such as the one that I went to.
And we took tests for two or three days out there and we got acquainted with campusology, what we would be expected to know.
We were issued a little booklet about four inches by six inches called the Cadence.
And in there was the history of Texas A&M as well as pictures of all of the buildings on campus
a description of the buildings, when they were built, and who they were named for, and you better, by God, remember that.
And they emphasized that.
Fortunately, there were no upperclassmen, pissheads, as we call the sophomores.
They kept them away from us so we could concentrate on what we were out there for, and that was to learn what was expected of us at Texas A&M.
And we started drilling right off, and I had a leg up because I'd done all that kind of stuff at Beaumont High.
Our PE coach was a former Navy commander, World War II, and he gave us all of the manual of arms and the squads left, squads right, about face.
We had all of that, so that was not a problem for me.
A lot of the boys from the country, they didn't know their left foot from their right foot, and they had a little bit of difficulty.
But the sophomores straightened them out a little bit later.
So you're out there four days, then you come back.
We went back and forth by bus every day.
Oh, okay.
How long was it before the upperclassmen got to the campus and you all got into the real world of being an Aggie freshman?
They got here the week after we did, after our orientation was over.
We reported something like the 7th of September, and the upperclassmen reported around the 14th or 15th.
And of course, keep in mind, this was the first year that freshman athletes had lived on campus, and the regular freshman class was separated out
to the air base, and that made it logistically difficult for the upperclassmen to find freshmen to harass.
And the senior athletes made it known to the other upperclassmen very quickly, these are our freshmen, you keep your damn hands off of them.
If anybody's going to beat ass, we're going to beat ass.
Now, y'all were in what dorm?
Hart Hall.
Describe the routine, particularly your room, and what it was like.
I lived in I-9 Hart Hall.
Hart Hall was a U-shaped building with the bottom of the U truncated on both sides.
It was three stories, and it had ramps.
ramps A through I, and there was a stairwell going up the middle of each ramp, and there were two rooms on each side, no, four rooms on each side on each floor, and the rooms shared a bath.
So that you're on the I ramp third floor?
That's right.
And...
Who was your fish old lady and what?
Initially, my fish old lady was Robert Schaefer, Buddy Schaefer, who was a football player and track man.
And they just kind of threw us all into, they matched us up.
They didn't do it alphabetically.
I don't know what method Colonel Andy used for the track people, but he said,
If you want to change roommates, if you know somebody from another town, you go right ahead.
Just keep me informed so I'll know where you are.
And then he asked me later on, after about three or four days rooming with Buddy, Buddy had found a hometown buddy that he'd prefer to room with.
And Colonel Landy asked me if I would like to room with his son, Wally.
And I said, well, sure.
So Wally and I started out rooming together for a couple of three weeks.
And then a hometown friend of mine who was a sophomore, Walter Evans, he had been a football and track teammate for my high school.
And he, his daddy, was a car dealer.
And Walter
would bring an old clunker used car off of his daddy's car to school.
And since we were from the same hometown,
